        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1893-02-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1893-02-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="536" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d536">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Wharton</persName> to
                                Prince <persName type="to">Cantacuzène</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1893-02-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 28,
                                    1893</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have had the honor to receive your note
                            of the 20th instant, in reply to Mr. Foster’s of the 16th, concerning
                            the refusal of the Russian consul-general at New York to visé the United
                            States passport of Mrs. Mannie Lerin.</p>
                <p>In view of your statement that the visa in question was refused because
                            Mrs. Lerin “declared herself to be a Jewess,” and in accordance with the
                            instructions of the Imperial Government “interdicting to visé passports
                            of foreign Jews, with the exception of certain cases under which Mrs.
                            Lerin can not be placed,” I limit myself for the present to
                            acknowledging your communication under the reserve necessarily imposed
                            upon the Government by its constitution and laws, and by its just
                            expectation that its certification of the character of American
                            citizenship will be respected.</p>
                <p>Accept, sir, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William E. Wharton</hi>,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
